where people who use the label may not necessarily be transphobic or biphobic themselves, the label is just redundant and its easier to use bisexual because it has existed since the early 20th century and even before and the definition was modified to mean "two or more genders" or "attraction to someone no matter the sex" where like. no matter what you're assigned as at birth, the latter definition would easily cover all genders

faceonfire 22-Feb-20 10:53 AM
trans identity is a scam
having the trans label pushed on us by media and getting called "trans man," etc. at every turn instead of just our gender is another form of degendering/Othering
trans is a categorical term that simply describes conditions of life (edited)
many people I've known have felt at odds with the trans label or like it's an ineffective term for various reasons, and I can't blame em
"Trans" is pushed on us at every turn by both cis society and trans communities to the point where we cant just be whatever gender we are
it's an everpresent reminder that we're not truly our gender
its tricky because we need the trans identity to advocate for our rights and form communities, but that same identity becomes alienating when you want to be seen as more than just trans
if you've always felt like a man or a woman, it can definitely feel weird to speak like you've "crossed over" which the word transgender implies
if you're nonbinary it can feel weird because you still relate to aspects of your assigned gender, you simply dont experience having a gender, or being transgender is always presented as such a binary thing
starting to see trans people as members of our gender groups who simply have unfortunate birth circumstances would probably be a step forward
where "trans" can finally just be a matter of fact descriptor, not something that overrides everything else about you

@xxxthrashpunkrat420xxx I've identified as a trans man for over a year because of extremely traumatic events I have went through; that made me violently hate being female and honestly feel traumatized just at the fact that there is female parts under my clothes. I just wanted to share that because yeah, a lot of people identify as nonbinary or whatever else because of trauma.
And actually going through a time of thinking I was trans helped me in my journey. Now I am just proud and happy to be a gender nonconforming woman.

For a lot of people their voice and how they talk are an important part of their identity and self-image, but that's more of a thing in the trans community I'd say
And it should be clarified that passing isn't the goal for everyone, voice or otherwise

꧁꧂Hark ꧁꧂ 05-Jul-20 08:42 PM
i'll just respond here because IDK if i got blocked but i typed it all up anyway so
Yeah I mean I'm not gonna lie I haven't run into a person in the wild that knows a thing or 2 about feminism but does not agree it is a fight for ALL women regardless of biological sex in years, trans people have been historically victimized just as long as but more so than biological women this whole time- targeted during the holocaust, Berlin where there were libraries of information on it being burned along with Jewish texts, people not conforming to their genders have existed all over the world in hundreds of different communities and it was never thought of as 'weird' until the colonization of 'western ideaology' cemented the immutable ideas we now call gender. Still today trans people are legally denied healthcare, housing, and can be murdered after/during consensual sex in America in what the courts rule 'trans panic defense', which is in the same realm as the rape culture that plagues Western Sensibilities but sees less media attention, justice and consideration because they do not have the same legal or social protections- but the solidarity and protection afforded transfolx thru feminism at least helps the social side.
The American Medical Organization, The World Health Organization, Planned Parenthood, The UK National Health Service, The American Psychiatric Association, the Endocrine Society, The American College of Physicians, The American College of Obstetricians and Gynecologists, The American Academy of Nursing, The American Academy of Child and Infant Psychiatry all recognize trans people are valid and it is not a mental illness or autogynophelia, as previously imagined
Before Hawaii was colonized for example, had a 'trans' community by a different name, and it wasn't thought of as abnormal or needing to be differentiated because people coexisted and supported each other as much they would any other neighbor, the necessity to 'other' wasn't introduced until long after our Western Values plagued what was previously a happy-on-their-own group of people. article for reference https://gayety.co/a-brief-history-of-hawaiis-ancient-gay-culture/ (edited)
Gayety Staff
A Brief History of Hawaii’s Ancient Gay Culture
Few people appreciate just how gay-friendly Polynesia was before European contact. Even Captain Cook, who passed through Hawaii, noted in his journals same-same (Aikane) relationships as well as transgender people (Mahu). The ancient Hawaiians weren’t uptight about relationshi...
Fun Fact: On top of the whole "gender is sex" fiasco, chromosomes also don't work like that, nor are the sex chromosomes the sole determinant of biological sex. Other chromosomal conditions occur regularly--XXY, also known as Klinefelter syndrome, is more common than schizophrenia. And things like androgen resistance can cause a genetically male individual to develop an entirely 100% female body. Other things happen, too.
biology is messy af. Our spine literally can't hold up our heads for the amount of time we're alive. No one really knows how the brain even works. Sometimes the immune system just attacks part of the body for no reason. The poorly designed flesh sacks we call our bodies likely did not happen to produce a purely binary, immutable concept called gender-- and we should not pick and choose who we give our support to based off of it.
and yeah i'd be down to watch a video of yours sometime @Nodus, but if trans women don't have the same rights as cis people today and still aren't welcome in many of these places I'm going to turn my nose up @ the notion feminist spaces don't have space for them either.
that's allyship imo

Funeral Parade of Roses (薔薇の葬列 Bara no Sōretsu) is a 1969 Japanese drama directed and written by Toshio Matsumoto, as a loose adaptation of Oedipus Rex set in the gay underground of 1960's Japan. Considered an exemplar of Japanese New Wave, the film combines arthouse, documentary, and experimental techniques, blending fact with fiction to portray the struggles of transgender women and gay men in post-occupation Japan. JaceyLM 15-Sep-20 10:33 PM
You are operating under the assumption that transpeople cannot be the gender they feel they are because you believe biology is correct, that “if you’re born a girl, you’re a girl, if you’re born a boy, you’re a boy.” It is just not that simple. For cis-people, this is certainly correct. They identify the gender they are born as and experience no dysphoria. If a cis-male took estrogen and transitioned to being a woman, he would experience dysphoria because he knows he is not a woman. Transpeople experience dysphoria because there is a disconnect between their brain and their body. Their brain and nerve endings scream “I’m this gender! Why do I have these parts?” People who transition to their correct gender, they are reportedly happy and comfortable in their skin. Your ideology of telling people to “love themselves” and accept the body they have, is damaging. If a transperson who has dysphoria and chooses to follow your message, they wouldn’t be happy. They would be miserable. Most likely, they would commit suicide. In the US, 41% of transpeople have attempted to commit suicide. The LGBT community are 10 times higher than the general population to attempt or commit suicide. This is due to discrimination from peers, family, high rates of unemployment, sexual assault and being murdered just for being who they are. Gender dysphoria is a recognised medical condition. I highly encourage you to read the DSM-5. We need support and allies. TLDR; the treatment for gender dysphoria is not self-love or self acceptance. Encouraging people to follow this path is encouraging people to be someone they are not. This will make them miserable and cause them to commit suicide. The recommended treatment for gender dysphoria is transitioning, which allows them to be who they really are. This has been backed by the medical community and numerous studies done on the topic. I’d rather trust these sources than a random stranger on DV. (edited)

brynn 27-Sep-20 10:03 PM
There exists an ugly myth that because the prefix “bi” means “two”, bisexuality reinforces the concept of a gender binary and only recognizes two genders — men and women. It is often assumed this also excludes trans men and women. In light of these myths, pansexuality is sometimes put forth as an enlightened, gender-inclusive alternative to bisexuality, because “pan” means “all”, and therefore subverts the gender binary.
Bisexuality is a whole, fluid identity. Do not assume that bisexuality is binary or duogamous in nature: that we have "two" sides or that we must be involved simultaneously with both genders to be fulfilled human beings. In fact, don’t assume that there are only two genders. Do not mistake our fluidity for confusion, irresponsibility, or an inability to commit. Do not equate promiscuity, infidelity, or unsafe sexual behavior with bisexuality. Those are human traits that cross all sexual orientations. Nothing should be assumed about anyone’s sexuality, including your own. We are angered by those who refuse to accept our existence; our issues; our contributions; our alliances; our voice. It is time for the bisexual voice to be heard.” This manifesto is a fundamental piece of bisexual history and culture. It explicitly denounces the idea that bisexuality means an attraction to only two genders, and the idea that there are only two genders. Yes, “bi” means “two”. The duality of the “bi” in “bisexual” refers to the combination of homosexual and heterosexual attractions - some people extend this to a definition of bisexuality as “attraction to genders similar to and different from one’s own”.
Bi means heterosexual + homosexual, not two genders.
That's where the slur bihet comes in !
Pansexual people may refer to themselves as gender-blind, asserting that gender and sex are not determining factors in their romantic or sexual attraction to others. Pansexuality may be considered a sexual orientation in its own right or a branch of bisexuality, to indicate an alternative sexual identity.

Speaking of supportive family members, I struggled so much growing up in a country with zero gay cultural presence(I'm from saudi arabia). Didn't know what was wrong with me and genuinely thought i was alone. The internet was all i had and that was not good for my 11 year old brain. Basically, I highly suspect my 7 year old nephew might be gay, and i'm kind of proud of the fact that I'll be the guiding figure I never had. Generation Z is the first generation of lgbt people in my country who are shamelessly proud of who they are, and that has everything to do of the sacrifices and struggles of those of us in the west. Despite all of America's issues, I am still grateful for it's lgbt community for starting this movement for the rest of the world. I don't think we show appreciation the people who fought for us in the 60s, 70s, and 80s enough

The Response of the Menstrual Cycle to Initiation of Hormonal Thera...
Purpose: Transition from female to male gender after initiation of hormonal therapy involves both phenotypic and physiological changes. The response to treatment can vary widely from person to person. In this study, we looked at the response of the menstrual ...
The initiation of low to moderate testosterone was sufficient in leading to menstrual cessation in the majority of patients by 6 months and nearly all by 1 year. There was individual variability in the time to cessation with little correlation to testosterone dose.

Non-Binary DefinedMost people – including most transgender people – are either male or female. But some people don't neatly fit into the categories of "man" or "woman," or “male” or “female.” For example, some people have a gender that blends elements of being a man or a woman...
Cisgender
Cisgender (sometimes cissexual, often abbreviated to simply cis) is a term for people whose gender identity matches their sex assigned at birth. For example, someone who identifies as a woman and was assigned female at birth is a cisgender woman. The term cisgender is the oppo...

B A T H O R Y 22-Nov-20 10:58 AM
okay so
theres actually a huge debate in the LGBTQ community rn about this
pansexuality means you are attarcted to ALL genders
where as BIsexual means you are attracted to men and women (or in some cases two specific genders), but it does not mean exclusively bi people can still be attracted to trans/nonbinary just the same (edited)
now allow me to explain further
some people make the argument that bisexuality has always included non-binary and trans, and that pansexuality makes bisexual seem like a transphobic label, therefore it is both biphobic and transphobic.
NOT ACCORDING TO ME
that is just what some people are saying, most of the time terms are just used interchangeably
people go back and forth saying "bisexuality is bad because it excludes trans people" (not true) "pansexuality is bad because it fetishizes trans folk" (not true)
Honestly, its just whatever label that person feels more comfortable with, I personally label myself as bisexual, some people feelmore comfortable with the pansexual label
i find comfort in the bisexual flag because i mean, i can love anyone regardless of gender, but i find i tend to lean more toward masculine women and feminine men, but not specifically trans folk. Not to say i havent ever been attracted to trans folk, for ex one of my first serious relationships was with someone who used they/them pronouns
plus i discovered more about my sexuality by falling in love with men than i did with women, which is why i identify more with the bisexual label than a pansexual label simply because i tend to be more attracted to men (edited)

“But ‘bi’ means ‘two.’” This is the most used “gotcha” used to “prove” bisexuality is exclusive and binary — and one of my biggest pet peeves. “Bi” can be a misleading prefix to those unfamiliar with bisexual history (we’ve been describing bisexuality in terms of attraction regardless of gender since the 1970s). Pansexuals and bisexuals have the same experiences, but pan literally means bi without a preference. brynn “But ‘bi’ means ‘two.’” This is the most used “gotcha” used to “prove” bisexuality is exclusive and binary — and one of my biggest pet peeves. “Bi” can be a misleading prefix to those unfamiliar with bisexual history (we’ve been describing bisexuality in terms of attraction regardless of gender since the 1970s). With context and the community around it, though, we can better understand it. If we only look at semantics (and ignored all other meanings for the prefix), “bi means two” is a no brainer, but identities aren’t just strings of letters. Even if they were, not every word is precise and literal

OriginOfStyx 25-Dec-20 08:42 PM
I have had a lifelong desire to be asexual, but it is more due to a frustration in the nature of human desire. At least for me I think there is an obvious beauty to the human body, but I am simultaneously disturbed by bodily functions, which is a conflict I can't resolve. Trying to satiate human desire is like drinking salt water, the more you drink the thirstier you become. I would rather live a life of asceticism and focus on fostering an ethic of self-cultivation (which is a lifelong journey and process) than get stuck in a cycle of human desire and dissatisfaction.
